{
  "message": "test(fuzz): broaden einsum_subscripts target with batch + path coverage\n\nThe previous einsum fuzz target only invoked `UFuncArray::einsum`\non three fixed 1-D/2-D operands, which left a lot of einsum's\npublic surface area unexercised by libFuzzer. Expand the harness\nso each random subscript string is funneled through every public\neinsum entry point, with both flat and batched operand shapes.\n\nOperand setup:\n- a: (2,3), b: (3,4), c: (4,2) \u2014 chosen so a chain like\n  `ij,jk,kl->il` actually contracts cleanly when the random\n  subscripts happen to be valid.\n- batch_a: (2,2,3), batch_b: (2,3,4) \u2014 drives the batched-matmul\n  paths, including the broadcasting/ellipsis machinery.\n- scalar: 0-D operand, kept from the previous harness for the\n  bare-output corner case.\n- Operand construction now uses `let Ok(...) else return;` so\n  shape/value mismatches abort cleanly instead of unwrap-panicking\n  inside the harness on future shape edits.\n\nAPI coverage now per fuzz iteration:\n- `einsum`: 1, 2, and 3 flat operands; batched 1- and 2-operand;\n  scalar 1- and 2-operand.\n- `einsum_path`: 2- and 3-operand flat, batched 2-operand, and\n  scalar 2-operand \u2014 exercises the contraction planner without\n  going through full execution.\n- `einsum_optimized` with both `\"greedy\"` and `\"optimal\"` planner\n  strategies on flat 3-operand and batched 2-operand inputs.\n\nAlso seed `fuzz/corpus/einsum_subscripts/` with 18 hand-written\nseeds covering the most representative shapes the fuzzer would\notherwise need to discover from scratch:\n\n- Trivial: total sum (`->`), row sum (`ij->i`), diagonal extract,\n  trace, transpose, dot product.\n- Implicit-output forms: implicit matmul, ellipsis implicit,\n  hadamard.\n- Multi-operand: matmul, outer product, triple-chain\n  contraction, batch matmul both explicit and via ellipsis.\n- Ellipsis variants: ellipsis transpose, ellipsis batch matmul,\n  repeated output index.\n- Negative-path seeds: `seed_invalid_multiple_arrow` (two `->`\n  tokens) and `seed_invalid_stray_dot` to make sure the parser's\n  error branches stay reachable from the corpus alone.\n\nNet effect: substantially broader path coverage per iteration\nplus a representative starting corpus, so the fuzzer doesn't\nhave to rediscover basic einsum syntax on every fresh run.\n\nCo-Authored-By: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>",
